    <text>
        <body>
            <head>189. Telegram From the Embassy in <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> to the Department of State<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d189fn1">Source: Carter Library, National Security
                    Affairs, Staff Material, <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle
                        East</placeName>, Subject File, Box 89, <placeName
                        corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>: 2/77–6/78. Confidential;
                    Priority.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Tunis</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-06-29T07:00:00+00:00">June 29, 1977, 0700Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>4546. <gloss target="#t_NEA_1">NEA</gloss> for <persName corresp="recqQ6Wv2eONUThFu"
                    >Atherton</persName>, <gloss target="#t_PM_1">PM</gloss> for <persName
                    corresp="recIbApOzPGX7c1z0">Gelb</persName> and <persName
                    corresp="rec6gb4ZoTJRdh63o">Ericson</persName>. Subject: Visit of Director, DSAA
                to Tunis. Ref: CHUSLOT 4489.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d189fn2">Not
                    found.</note>
            </p>
            <p>1. Summary. We were honored and pleased to have had LTG <persName
                    corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName>, Director, DSAA visit <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>, 24–26 June. General <persName
                    corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName> was the bearer of some exceptionally
                good news to our <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName> friends
                (and to us as well). We discussed <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 77 <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credit and possible end-of-year credits; the Chaparral, Vulcan and FAAR
                purchases; and a general wrap-up of <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisian</placeName> military requirements. End summary.</p>
            <p>2. LTG <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName> attended the <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName> Armed Forces 21st anniversary
                dinner, visited the <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName>
                Military Academy, and was most warmly received at a dinner for him, hosted by Sec
                Gen of Defense Alouini. LTG <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName>
                additionally held very profitable discussions with Defense Minister <persName
                    corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> and his deputy, Ahmed Bennour.</p>
            <p>3. General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName> discussed the
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName>
                <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 77 <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credit agreement, indicating that it would indeed be $25 million as we had
                hoped. Apparently the additional $10 million in <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss>
                77 credit authorization for <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> is included in the Presidential Determination request and
                we understood that it should be received in the near future.<note n="3" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d189fn3">See <ref target="#d191">Document 191</ref>.</note> We further
                understand from General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName> that
                if <gloss target="#t_GOT_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">GOT</placeName>
                </gloss> desires additional end <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 77 credit, we can
                have Ambassador <persName corresp="reclCf8vZH8axhvIA">Hedda</persName> ready to sign
                an additional <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credit agreement before 30 Sept. The Tunisians were of course elated <pb
                    facs="0475" n="454" xml:id="pg_454"/> over this news which will permit them to
                sign their FAAR and Vulcan (see SecState from CHUSLOT 4489) Letter of Offer and
                Acceptance (LOA) as soon as the paperwork can get to us.</p>
            <p>4. We also informed the Tunisians of the 28-month delivery schedule in their
                Chaparral buy (vice 30 months). General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc"
                    >Fish</persName> hand-carried their FAAR radar LOA and discussed the realization
                of a complete air defense system in the 1979 time frame.</p>
            <p>5. General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName> mentioned to the
                Tunisians the possibility of a reduction in missile costs for their Chaparral buy
                but made no firm commitment until legal clarification is received.</p>
            <p>6. Ministers <persName corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> and Bennour, as
                well as the Chief of Staff of the <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisian</placeName> Armed Forces, were most appreciative of the fine effort of
                General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName>. We too appreciate
                State Department’s backing <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">DOD</orgName>
                </gloss> and helping the Tunisians realize their much needed defense
                requirements.</p>
            <p>7. The Tunisians took the opportunity to outline to us some of their out-year
                military hardware requirements such as two missile and M48A5 tanks. With good
                financial planning based on the news of credit availability, the Tunisians will be
                well on the road to achieving their modernization program.</p>
            <p>8. My personal thanks to the Department for the fine support it is giving Defense
                Department in assisting <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>.
                General <persName corresp="recGmMCJWIMTAeYVc">Fish</persName>’s visit was one of the
                most welcome and profitable we have had.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recoYGZSMuqMPW41n">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Mulcahy</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
